{"status":"success","result":"Great question — here are my honest thoughts:\n\n*Where the team approach really shines for Jarvis:*\n• Complex, parallelizable tasks (research + coding + review happening simultaneously)\n• Tasks that benefit from specialized \"lenses\" — e.g. a security expert reviewing code while a UX expert reviews flows\n• Keeping concerns separated so no single agent gets overwhelmed with context\n\n*Where it gets tricky:*\n• *Coordination overhead* — agents need to sync, and if the communication layer is clunky, you spend more time managing the team than doing work\n• *Context bleed* — agents can step on each other if task boundaries aren't crisp\n• *Cost* — multiple agents burning tokens in parallel adds up fast\n\n*My main recommendation:*\nDon't default to a team just because it sounds powerful. Start with a *strong single agent* and only spin up teammates when there's a clear bottleneck or a genuinely parallel workload. The best teams are formed *reactively* — when the lead agent hits a wall and says \"I need a specialist here.\"\n\n*For Jarvis specifically* — since it's an always-on assistant, I'd think about teams as *on-demand surge capacity* rather than a permanent structure. Spin them up for a task, synthesize, dissolve.\n\nWhat direction is Claude CLI taking it right now? I'm curious what's already in place.","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
