{"status":"success","result":"Okay I had a thorough look! Here's what I'm thinking:\n\n*What's working really well:*\n• The `[ESCALATE: reason]` marker system is clean and simple — Jarvis knows his limits and signals clearly\n• The file-based request queue is solid, no tight coupling between Jarvis and Andy\n• Human confirmation before escalation is a nice touch — prevents Andy from being spammed\n\n*The core challenge you identified — teaching Jarvis *when* to ask:*\n\nRight now escalation is fairly binary — Jarvis either handles it or kicks it to Andy. The risk is *under-escalation* (Jarvis confidently hallucinating instead of admitting he needs help) and *over-escalation* (Andy gets pinged for things Jarvis could handle with a bit more prompting).\n\nA few ideas worth exploring:\n\n• *Confidence scoring* — instead of a hard yes/no, have Jarvis rate his confidence (1-10) and auto-escalate below a threshold, no user confirmation needed for obvious cases\n• *Skill tagging* — explicitly tell Jarvis what Andy's superpowers are (web search, file ops, code execution, scheduling) so he escalates on *capability* not just uncertainty\n• *Silent escalation option* — for time-sensitive things, skip the yes/no and just let Andy run in parallel, then surface whichever answer comes first\n• *Post-mortem feedback* — when Andy corrects or expands on a Jarvis answer, log that pattern so the prompts can be refined over time\n\nWhat's the biggest pain point right now — is it Jarvis over-escalating, under-escalating, or something else?","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
